  "prompt": "What books should every teenager read?",
  "response": "Every teenager should read a variety of books that broaden their perspectives, inspire critical thinking, and encourage self-discovery. Here\u2019s a list of timeless and impactful books across genres:\n\n### Classics and Literature\n1. **\"To Kill a Mockingbird\" by Harper Lee** \u2013 Explores themes of justice, morality, and racial inequality.\n2. **\"1984\" by George Orwell** \u2013 A dystopian novel that delves into themes of surveillance and authoritarianism.\n3. **\"The Catcher in the Rye\" by J.D. Salinger** \u2013 A coming-of-age story about identity and alienation.\n4. **\"Pride and Prejudice\" by Jane Austen** \u2013 A witty exploration of love, class, and societal expectations.\n5. **\"The Great Gatsby\" by F. Scott Fitzgerald** \u2013 A critique of the American Dream and the Jazz Age.\n\n### Personal Growth and Self-Discovery\n6. **\"The Alchemist\" by Paulo Coelho** \u2013 A philosophical novel about pursuing dreams and finding purpose.\n7. **\"Man\u2019s Search for Meaning\" by Viktor E. Frankl** \u2013 A profound exploration of resilience and finding meaning in life.\n8. **\"The Perks of Being a Wallflower\" by Stephen Chbosky** \u2013 A heartfelt story about navigating adolescence and mental health.\n\n### Social Issues and Diversity\n9. **\"The Hate U Give\" by Angie Thomas** \u2013 A powerful novel addressing police brutality and racial injustice.\n10. **\"I Am Malala\" by Malala Yousafzai** \u2013 An inspiring memoir about standing up for education and equality.\n11. **\"Between the World and Me\" by Ta-Nehisi Coates** \u2013 A letter to the author\u2019s son about race, identity, and America.\n\n### Fantasy and Adventure\n12. **\"Harry Potter\" series by J.K. Rowling** \u2013 A magical journey of friendship, courage, and growth.\n13. **\"The Hobbit\" and \"The Lord of the Rings\" by J.R.R. Tolkien** \u2013 Epic tales of adventure and heroism.\n14. **\"The Hunger Games\" trilogy by Suzanne Collins** \u2013 A gripping story about survival, rebellion, and justice.\n\n### Science Fiction and Thought-Provoking Reads\n15. **\"Fahrenheit 451\" by Ray Bradbury** \u2013 Explores censorship, conformity, and the power of knowledge.\n16. **\"Brave New World\" by Aldous Huxley** \u2013 A cautionary tale about technology, control, and humanity.\n17. **\"Ender\u2019s Game\" by Orson Scott Card** \u2013 A story of strategy, morality, and leadership.\n\n### Non-Fiction and Inspiration\n18. **\"Sapiens: A Brief History of Humankind\" by Yuval Noah Harari** \u2013 A fascinating exploration of human history.\n19. **\"Atomic Habits\" by James Clear** \u2013 A practical guide to building good habits and breaking bad ones.\n20. **\"Educated\" by Tara Westover** \u2013 A memoir about overcoming adversity and the power of education.\n\n### Poetry and Creative Writing\n21. **\"Milk and Honey\" by Rupi Kaur** \u2013 A collection of poignant and empowering poetry.\n22. **\"The Sun and Her Flowers\" by Rupi Kaur** \u2013 Explores themes of growth, healing, and self-love.\n23. **\"Leaves of Grass\" by Walt Whitman** \u2013 Celebrates individuality, nature, and the human spirit.\n\n### Graphic Novels and Illustrated Stories\n24. **\"Persepolis\" by Marjane Satrapi** \u2013 A graphic memoir about growing up during the Iranian Revolution.\n25. **\"Maus\" by Art Spiegelman** \u2013 A profound graphic novel about the Holocaust and its impact.\n\nThese books can help teenagers develop empathy, critical thinking, and a deeper understanding of themselves and the world around them. Encourage them to explore genres and discover what resonates with them!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
